:content
<p>
<a name=matrice_colonne>
<a name=matrice_ligne>
<a name=matrice_carree>
An $m_m×$m_n A matrix is a <em>line matrix</em> if $m_m=1,
or <em>column matrix</em> if $m_n=1. A is a <em>square matrix</em> if
$m_m=$m_n.
<p>
<a name=diagonale>
IN a matrix A=($m_a<sub>$m_i$m_j</sub>), the coefficients $m_a<sub>11</sub>,
$m_a<sub>22</sub>, $m_a<sub>33</sub> ... are <em>diagonal</em> coefficients.
A is a <em>diagonal</em> matrix if all its non-diagonal coefficients are zero.
<p>
<a name=triangulaire>
The matrix A=($m_a<sub>$m_i$m_j</sub>) is <em>upper-triangular</em>
(resp. <em>lower-triangular</em>) if all its coefficients below (resp. above)
the diagonal are zero, that is, $m_a<sub>$m_i$m_j</sub>&nbsp;=&nbsp;0 if $m_i &gt; $m_j
(resp. if $m_i &lt; $m_j).
<p>
<a name=trace>
The <em>trace</em> of a matrix A=($m_a<sub>$m_i$m_j</sub>) of dimension $m_m&times;$m_n
is the sum of diagonal coefficients&#58;
<p><center>
  trace(A) = 
!insmath \sum_{i=1}^{\min(m,n)}a_{ii}

</center><p>
<b>Remark</b>. Although the definitions of diagonal, trangular and trace are
valid for matrices of arbitrary dimensions, in general they are interesting
only for square matrices.
